# Commits, changelog, versioning

## Commit style

- Conventional-ish short subjects: `feat: ...`, `fix: ...`, `chore: ...`, `docs: ...`, `refactor: ...`, `perf: ...`, `test: ...`, `build: ...`, `ci: ...`.
- Subject <= 72 chars, lowercase after the prefix, no trailing period.
- Body optional but preferred for anything non-trivial; explain the "why", not the "what".
- No emojis anywhere in commit subjects or bodies.
- Never reference secrets, tokens, or internal URLs.

## What NOT to commit

- `dist/` — build output; listed in `.gitignore`.
- `pdf/`, `samples/out*/` — render outputs, large binary PDFs/PNGs.
- `node_modules/`.
- Any `.env`, `credentials.json`, or files that look like secrets. If you need to commit a file that contains a token-looking string for testing, pause and flag it for a human.

## User-visible changes

When a change is user-visible (new flag, new command, output format change, new markdown feature, design parser behavior change):

1. Bump `version` in [package.json](package.json) according to semver.
2. Add an entry to [docs/changelog.md](docs/changelog.md) under a new version heading.
3. Update any affected doc page(s) per [60-build-assets-and-docs.mdc](.cursor/rules/60-build-assets-and-docs.mdc).
4. Land these three changes in the same PR. Release tagging happens later (see release workflow).

## Release tag parity

The `publish.yml` workflow at [.github/workflows/publish.yml](.github/workflows/publish.yml) asserts that the GitHub release tag (with the leading `v` stripped) equals `package.json` `version`. The release will fail if they diverge.

- Tag format: `vX.Y.Z`. No pre-release suffix unless you've already updated `package.json` to match (e.g. tag `v0.2.0-beta.1` requires `"version": "0.2.0-beta.1"`).

## Dist is never committed

The build step runs in CI on every PR and at release time. Never commit `dist/` to short-circuit CI.
